        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-08-16T09:54:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-08-16T09:54:00-05:00" n="795"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d795">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">890F.24/8–1644: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister Resident in Saudi Arabia</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Moose</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Jidda</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-08-16T18:00:00+03:06"
                            >August 16, 1944—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received August 17—2:07 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>251. Message concerning maintenance at all times in Saudi Arabia of 3 months’
                    stocks of cereals, tea and sugar contained in next to last paragraph of
                    Department’s 158, August 14, 7 p.m.<note n="32" xml:id="d795fn32">See footnote
                        31, <ref target="#pg_727">p. 727</ref>.</note> was today conveyed both
                    verbally and in writing to Minister of Finance, now Acting Foreign Minister. He
                    expressed pleasure and predicted that King would be gratified at action of
                    United States Government. In response to question Minister opined that if plan
                    is put into effect promptly and if Saudi Government can draw requirements from
                    stocks in Arabia plan for purchase of food stuffs described in my 247 August 14,
                    5 p.m. will be dropped.</p>
                <p>Aramco representative greatly relieved since he thinks Saudi Government will
                    relax pressure for additional help from oil company.</p>
                <p>My British colleague was informed of the message before it was delivered. He
                    protested verbally stating that action of United States Government was not
                    cooperation and that he could not agree to acceptance of King’s statement of
                    needs. He also produced figures to show that with joint supply of cereals
                    limited to 40,000 tons, cereal imports into Saudi Arabia this year will total
                    68,700 tons. A despatch<note n="33" xml:id="d795fn33">Despatch 208, August 17,
                        not printed.</note> will explain why I consider his figures misleading.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Cairo for AEMME reference Cairo’s August 15, 1 p.m.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Moose</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
